1361","Abt 1318":"about 1318","20 May 1349":"20 May 1349","1391":"1391","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Ewelme, South Oxfordshire District, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Langley Street, Norfolk, England":"Langley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Kerdeston was born about 1318, in Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William Kerdeston 2nd Lord Kerdeston and Margaret Bacon. She married John de Burghersh about 1343, in Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 20 May 1349, at the age of 32, and was buried in Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1318–20 May 1349":"umbes 1318–20. mai 1349","1318–1349":"1318–1349","1324–1349":"1324–1349","1343–1391":"1343–1391","1303–1361":"1303–1361","–1328":"–1328","1349":"1349","1303":"1303","1324":"1324","1343":"1343","29 September 1343":"29. september 1343","about 1343":"umbes 1343","1361":"1361","Abt 1318":"umbes 1318","20 May 1349":"20. mai 1349","1391":"1391","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ewelme, South Oxfordshire District, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Langley Street, Norfolk, England":"Langley, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1318–20 May 1349":"noin 1318–20. toukokuuta 1349","1318–1349":"1318–1349","1324–1349":"1324–1349","1343–1391":"1343–1391","1303–1361":"1303–1361","–1328":"–1328","1349":"1349","1303":"1303","1324":"1324","1343":"1343","29 September 1343":"29. syyskuuta 1343","about 1343":"noin 1343","1361":"1361","Abt 1318":"noin 1318","20 May 1349":"20. toukokuuta 1349","1391":"1391","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Ewelme, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ewelme, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun